  "answer": "The critic misreads the target's own explanation. The target explicitly interprets the Sea Peoples as 'desperate, uninfected refugees fleeing the disease-ridden core.' This is not an inconsistency but the core of the model: the pandemic depopulated the palace centers and their immediate hinterlands, destroying the economic and political structures. The armed groups with families and livestock originated from or were pushed out of the peripheries and pastoral zones that were not yet fully integrated into the dense urban trade networks where the pathogen was most intensely transmitted. Their military capacity is not contradictory because the pandemic's selective pressure fell hardest on the sedentary, specialized urban classes dependent on the palace trade system, not on mobile, less densely settled pastoral or peripheral communities. These groups could therefore remain uninfected precisely because they were not part of the high-contact urban core, and they mustered sufficient manpower to confront Egypt because they were the survivors of the systemic collapse, not its primary biological victims. The military conflict with Egypt is thus a downstream consequence of the pandemic-driven collapse, not a contradictory observation requiring ad hoc special pleading."
